        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "good question (and one i shouldve asked myself before), vim doesn't need this code because it includes `':'` in the default value for `isfname` on windows. Although it makes drive letters work, it creates issues as `':'` is not a valid windows filename char except directly after the drive letter.\r\n\r\nI understand your concern about adding special cases everywhere, but I feel like being able to handle drive letters is a basic feature for file completion on windows, as it is the basic component of any absolute file path (excluding UNC paths, but I don't think they are used nearly as much as drive letter paths).",
